Rating: 1
While this soup may be tasty, the traditional version does not use premade chicken stock or broth- the only substitute that would keep the flavor of the linguiça sausage would be a Spanish chorizo, if the Portuguese chouriço was unavailable. Substituting a different ethnic ingredient changes the recipe. Once you add pepperoncini, feta cheese, keilbasa sausage or other ethnic substitutions you can no longer call the soup Portuguese. The flavor is different. Eastern and western European flavors differ. Only as a last resort substitute and then call it an adaptation or Portuguese-like -please don't call it authentic. By the way, most countries have their own versions of Stone Soup

